===Usage notes===
This term is given as a native Korean equivalent of the Chinese first-person pronouns {{m|zh|我}} and {{m|zh|吾}} in plural contexts (Chinese not making the distinction morphologically) in three different sources of Korean-language interpretive ''{{w|gugyeol}}'' glosses to the Buddhist canon, made between the tenth and thirteenth centuries. Interpretive ''gugyeol'' encodes guidelines by which a Korean speaker could have read out a Classical Chinese text in its native Korean translation, much like Japanese {{w|kanbun}}. These three sources accordingly instruct the Korean reader to pronounce the Chinese first-person pronouns as {{m|oko|又}} or {{m|oko|于}}, allowing us to understand that this is the Old Korean word for "we; us".

The Middle Korean first-person plural pronoun {{m|okm|우리|tr=wuli|t=we; us}} is almost certainly derived from it, although the second syllable remains as of yet inexplicable.

